title: Add parameterized docker flag support for custom build android package script.
body:
### Description
<!-- Describe your changes. -->

This change adds parameterized docker run flag support for custom build android package script. 
p.s. This Android custom build script isn't included in the release. it's intended for usage by a user wanting to do a custom build. This script is not included in the python package of this release.

### Motivation and Context
<!-- - Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here. -->

Currently the suggested approach building custom Android ONNXRuntime library is based on the following script:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/main/tools/android_custom_build/build_custom_android_package.py

In this script, the docker run settings are set to require an interactive environment, with the flag "-it". Thus if running in a non-interactive environment, this would be an issue.

This change adds parameterized docker run flag support, so user can specify whether to run docker in an interactive/non-interactive environment. If the user doesn't specify the content of "--docker_interactive_mode_flag", the default behavior is the same as what has been set previously: Use flag "-it" to make it run in an interactive environment. If user wants to run this script non-interactively, they can specify with the command "--docker_interactive_mode_flag i" to make it run non-interactively.

The parameter is added along with description on how it would work, and suggested use cases.

Update: In the discussion under this PR, we decided to remove the `-it` flag in the end, as it is not necessary for working in a console (interactive envinironment) and works with building in non-interactive environment as well.

Session-aware and thread-safe CUDA profiler
body:
### Description
The existing CUDA profiler is neither session-aware, nor thread-safe. This PR ensures both.

### Motivation and Context
[PR 13549](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/13549) brought thread-safety and session-awareness to the ROCm profiler. This PR brings the same goodness to the CUDA profiler as well.

Sample outputs of a profiling run from the StableDiffusion model (this model was chosen because it requires orchestration of multiple sessions, and verifies that the profilers are now indeed session-aware) on both CUDA and ROCm EPs are attached, along with a script that checks that the trace files generated by the profile are well-formed.

Update 11/29: Updated the profile outputs. The older profile outputs exhibited an issue where some timestamps were wildly out of range, leading to problems visualizing the traces. The bug has been fixed and the profile outputs have been updated, along with an update to the check script to ensure that timestamps are monotonically increasing.

### Describe the issue

Hello,

There seems to be a problem with DML optimization on certain combinations of simple operators.
See the pytorch small example below to reproduce.
When this model is fed any random input, the output in y2 will be very different if ran on DMLProvider than if ran on CPU (or CUDA, or directly in pytorch).

If the last line of the model is replaced by `return (y2, y1)` then the output is the same as CPU.
If the first addition is removed, or the norm, or the slice, or anything else is changed, then the output is the same as CPU.
It's this particular combination that somehow gets a wrong output.

(I did get other combinations that also produce wrong outputs, let me know if you need more)

the problem is present in onnx current release (1.13.1) as well as latest HEAD.
also doesn't matter if using directml.dll 1.9 or 1.9.1

### To reproduce

```
import torch

class bug(torch.nn.Module):
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        self.conv1 = torch.nn.ConvTranspose1d(64, 32, 8, 4)
        self.conv2 = torch.nn.ConvTranspose1d(64, 32, 8, 4)
        self.norm = torch.nn.GroupNorm(4, 32)
        
    def forward(self, x):
        x = x + x

        y2 = self.conv2(x)
        y2 = self.norm(y2)
        y2 = torch.nn.functional.gelu(y2)

        y1 = self.conv1(x)
        y1 = y1[..., :4]
        y1 = torch.nn.functional.gelu(y1)

        return (y1, y2)


state = {}
state['conv1.weight'] = torch.randn(64, 32, 8)
state['conv1.bias'] = torch.randn(32)
state['conv2.weight'] = torch.randn(64, 32, 8)
state['conv2.bias'] = torch.randn(32)
state['norm.weight'] = torch.randn(32)
state['norm.bias'] = torch.randn(32)

model = bug()
model.load_state_dict(state)
model.eval()

with torch.no_grad():
```

title: Ryanunderhill/cxx api2
body:
### Description
<!-- Describe your changes. -->
New C++ style API that follows modern C++ conventions, like std::unique_ptr for ownership and references for non ownership & required parameters. It turns the C types into C++ types with methods, where deleting the type releases the resources.

As these new types are just the C types, a pointer to one is just a pointer. In the existing C++ wrappers, an Ort::Value is itself a structure holding a pointer to an OrtValue. Here you work directly with the OrtValue pointer.

After more initial reviews, I can convert some samples to use this new API, as samples are important to have. Plus, I can add documentation generation for the new header.

### Motivation and Context
<!-- - Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?-->
This is to solve these issues:
1. Users would get confused by the wrapped pointer types, with things like std::unique_ptr<Ort::Env> which is a pointer to a pointer.
2. Creating an empty wrapper type was done through a {nullptr} constructor. This is not standard C++ and would lead to people doing (1) above.
3. As the types were wrapped pointers, returning unowned wrapped pointers required some extra templates. This was harder to follow when looking at the code.
4. Needing to figure out an OrtAllocator parameter was an extra complexity. Now functions will return a std::string and require no allocator to be passed in (internally it uses std::string as an allocator).
5. Confusing way to detect empty objects, as they all look like values. An Ort::Value could hold a nullptr or it could hold a valid pointer. The new header works like standard C++.

Bonus features:
As the types are just the C API types, it interops with the C API with no extra effort. The existing wrappers required operators to return the C types from the wrapped types.

title: [Documentation] Clarify Cuda Operator OpSet compatibility support

labels.name: ep:CUDA
labels.description: issues related to the CUDA execution provider

body:
### Describe the documentation issue

We've recently worked through an issue where an inference model intended to only use Cuda supported operators would always fallback to CPU for just one operator, which docs list as Cuda supported.

Model built with OpSet 12
ArgMax operator always ran on CPU EP

https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/main/docs/OperatorKernels.md#cudaexecutionprovider
Lists ArgMax OpSet support as [1, 10] and 11+, suggesting any OpSet since 11 should be supported.

A lot of digging later, exporting the model with OpSet 11 does run on the Cuda EP (with no changes to the model itself).

The main clues, after building and debugging into the library was the comment under:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/e19163167ebab17ea06508e1d940f7e264073593/onnxruntime/core/framework/kernel_registry.cc#L122

As well as a specific mention for ArgMax: (which I really wish I'd found sooner...)
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/ac7538b909990f89f9bfebb325cd53c3d31cf158/onnxruntime/core/providers/cuda/reduction/reduction_ops.cc#L106

While this does appear to be a planned feature, as a new user it could be helpful to clarify under the compatibility page and/or the OperatorKernels table, as it may affect operators other than ArgMax?

A side issue that made this a little harder to understand is that a lot of the internal logging doesn't output under the C# runtime (doesn't react to verbose setting), which meant the VerifyEachNodeIsAssignedToAnEp logging was all we had to go on initially. Expanded documentation could help understand cases like this.

### Page / URL

https://onnxruntime.ai/docs/reference/compatibility.html

title: Improve performance of logits MatMul for first decoding run in BeamSearch
body:
### Description
In BeamSearch, for the first decoding run with the user-provided input sequence, the final logits MatMul projects the encoding of the entire batched sequence onto the vocab space (i.e.) the MatMul's input shapes are [B, S, H] * [H, vocab_size]. This is sub-optimal as we only need to project the encoding of the last token of the sequence in each batch (i.e.) the logits MatMul's inputs should be [B, 1, H] * [H, vocab_size] where the `1` will be the last token of that batch. Today, we do the costlier MatMul (using [B,S,H]) and then slice out the logits corresponding to the last token per-batch. 

To reduce the cost of the MatMul in the first decoding run, a new custom version of MatMul is proposed called `LastTokenMatMul` (the spec of which is defined to strictly adhere to something which we will see in decoding subgraphs) which will slice out the last token per-batch and then do the MatMul. This result will be consumed seamlessly in the `BeamSearch` kernel (no change required there). If the provided batch has only one token in it, the slicing is skipped and the operation becomes regular MatMul.

TODO:  Run some perf evaluations

### Motivation and Context
Improve performance of BeamSearch
